But on obtaining at length the object of his petition,his joy and grati- tude found atterance in the beautiful hymn called the fourth Eclogue, in which he hails the auspicious times just dawning on the world, and initiated by the consulship of his friend and patron Pollio. The sixth Eologue was composed in the fol- lowing year, a. o. 39, iu fulfilmeut ofia promise made to Varus. The eighth was written in the autumn of the same year in honor of Pollio, who had gained a brilliant victory over the Parthini, a people of Dalmatia. The two remaining Eclogues, the seventh and tenth, were probably composed in the two following years.

The Eologues established the reputation of the poet, and gained him at once ardent friends and admirers among the most powerful and the most cultivated of the Romans. Among these, besides his early aud fast friend, Pollio, were Octavian, Maecenas, Varius, Horace, and Propertius. These and all other educated Romans of the day regarded Virgil as already superior in many'respects to any poet who had yet appeared. It was most of all in the exquisite finish and har- mony of his hexameters that he exoelled all who had preceded him. The hexameter verse had been first introduced into the Latin language, at the close of the second Punic war, by the soldier and poet Ennius. But though distinguished by origi· nality, strength, and vigor, the poetry of Ennius was ,harsh and rugged to a degree which rendered it to the more culti- vated testes of later generations almost intolerable. Nor by the poets who suoceeded Ennius had any such improvement been made in the composition of Latin verse, as to admit of any comparison between them and their Grecian models.
